Chapter 1 — Introduction to Cloud Computing
1.1 What is Cloud Computing

Cloud computing is the delivery of computing resources and IT services over the internet instead of using locally owned physical infrastructure.

These services include:

Servers
Storage
Databases
Networking
Security
Software
Analytics
Artificial Intelligence services
Application hosting

Instead of purchasing and maintaining physical hardware, organizations rent infrastructure from cloud providers such as:

Amazon Web Services (AWS)
Microsoft Azure
Google Cloud Platform (GCP)
Simple Real-World Explanation

Traditionally, if a company wanted to host a website or application, they needed to:

purchase physical servers
build a data center
install networking devices
maintain cooling and power systems
manage hardware failures
upgrade infrastructure manually

Cloud computing removes this complexity.

Organizations can now:

launch servers in minutes
scale globally
automate deployments
pay only for usage

without managing physical infrastructure.

Real-World Analogy
Traditional Infrastructure

Imagine opening a restaurant.

You would need to:

buy land
construct the building
